WEBVTT

00:09.180 --> 00:12.440
Hi there! Welcome to
this video. Today we

00:12.440 --> 00:14.100
will learn how to
protect your personal

00:14.100 --> 00:17.280
data online. Personal
data does not

00:17.280 --> 00:20.000
disappear on its own.
You can take steps to

00:20.000 --> 00:23.260
stay safe and stay in
control. The goal of

00:23.260 --> 00:25.480
this video is to show
simple ways to

00:25.480 --> 00:27.840
protect your privacy.
We will look at

00:27.840 --> 00:30.240
privacy settings, app
permissions, safe

00:30.240 --> 00:32.140
sharing habits, and
deleting old

00:32.140 --> 00:35.360
information. These
small actions can

00:35.360 --> 00:39.120
make a big difference
. Protecting personal

00:39.120 --> 00:40.840
data means
controlling who can

00:40.840 --> 00:44.140
see it and how it is
used. When you use

00:44.140 --> 00:46.500
apps and websites,
they may collect and

00:46.500 --> 00:49.260
store information
about you. Privacy

00:49.260 --> 00:51.660
tools help you choose
what is shared and

00:51.660 --> 00:54.660
what is not. Many
apps have privacy

00:54.660 --> 00:58.860
settings like public,
friends, or only me.

00:58.920 --> 01:01.780
Public means many
people can see it.

01:02.060 --> 01:04.380
Choosing only friends
can reduce who sees

01:04.380 --> 01:07.500
your posts and
information. Before

01:07.500 --> 01:09.840
posting a photo,
check the background.

01:09.840 --> 01:12.080
Could it show your
school name, a street

01:12.080 --> 01:15.180
sign, or your house
number? Even if your

01:15.180 --> 01:17.420
face is not shown,
background details

01:17.420 --> 01:20.060
can still reveal
private information.

01:20.300 --> 01:22.200
Using a nickname
instead of a full

01:22.200 --> 01:25.420
name can help protect
privacy. Try not to

01:25.420 --> 01:27.080
share your address,
phone number, or

01:27.080 --> 01:30.060
school name in public
spaces. If a website

01:30.060 --> 01:31.840
asks for information
that feels

01:31.840 --> 01:35.180
unnecessary, stop and
ask a trusted adult.

01:35.660 --> 01:38.400
Apps sometimes ask
for permissions like

01:38.400 --> 01:41.400
access to your camera
, microphone, photos,

01:41.400 --> 01:43.800
or location.
Permissions should

01:43.800 --> 01:46.060
match what the app
needs. If a simple

01:46.060 --> 01:48.300
game asks for
location, that could

01:48.300 --> 01:51.360
be a warning sign.
Logging out helps

01:51.360 --> 01:53.480
protect your accounts
, especially on

01:53.480 --> 01:56.400
shared devices.
Locking your device

01:56.400 --> 01:58.620
with a passcode keeps
other people from

01:58.620 --> 02:01.400
opening your apps and
messages. These are

02:01.400 --> 02:03.420
simple steps that
protect your personal

02:03.420 --> 02:06.960
data every day. Old
accounts and old

02:06.960 --> 02:09.380
posts can keep your
data online longer

02:09.380 --> 02:12.480
than you expect. If
you no longer use an

02:12.480 --> 02:14.440
app, deleting the
account can reduce

02:14.440 --> 02:17.400
stored data. If you
posted something by

02:17.400 --> 02:19.880
mistake, deleting it
quickly can limit who

02:19.880 --> 02:23.140
sees it. If something
feels strange or

02:23.140 --> 02:26.940
unsafe, report it and
ask for help. You can

02:26.940 --> 02:29.340
tell a trusted adult,
a teacher, or a

02:29.340 --> 02:32.080
parent. Getting help
quickly is a smart

02:32.080 --> 02:34.560
way to protect your
data and your safety.

02:35.100 --> 02:37.480
One helpful habit is
to use a clean-up

02:37.480 --> 02:40.100
checklist. For
example, check

02:40.100 --> 02:42.400
privacy settings,
review permissions,

02:42.400 --> 02:45.900
delete old apps, and
log out. Doing a

02:45.900 --> 02:47.880
small clean-up
regularly keeps your

02:47.880 --> 02:51.500
digital footprint
smaller. In class,

02:51.500 --> 02:53.380
you will practice
this with a Fix This

02:53.380 --> 02:56.160
Profile activity. You
will look at a

02:56.160 --> 02:58.460
profile and find what
should be changed or

02:58.460 --> 03:01.180
hidden. This helps
you notice risky

03:01.180 --> 03:03.550
details and choose
safer settings.

03:07.790 --> 03:10.430
Let's recap.
Protecting personal

03:10.430 --> 03:12.890
data means sharing
carefully, using

03:12.890 --> 03:15.610
privacy settings, and
checking permissions.

03:15.850 --> 03:18.790
Log out, delete what
you do not need, and

03:18.790 --> 03:21.990
ask a trusted adult
when unsure. You have

03:21.990 --> 03:24.170
the power to control
your data and protect

03:24.170 --> 03:28.870
your privacy. Great
work! In this video,

03:28.870 --> 03:30.890
you learned practical
ways to protect your

03:30.890 --> 03:34.690
personal data online.
Next, use these tips

03:34.690 --> 03:36.830
in your classroom
activities and at

03:36.830 --> 03:39.270
home with a trusted
adult. Thank you for

03:39.270 --> 03:39.750
watching!

